ladders.explanation:
This sub-routine is the core of the greedy approach: after collecting all nodes via BFS, we iterate from deepest to shallowest, checking each node if it's an effective leaf (all children pruned or no children) and if its depth > L, then prune it. Intuition: Processing deeper nodes first ensures we remove violations at their source, potentially reducing need to prune higher nodes. For example, if a deep leaf violates, pruning it may make its parent an effective leaf but at lower depth—this might satisfy constraint without pruning parent. Step-by-step: 1) Have list of nodes with depths, sorted descending by depth. 2) For each node, if already pruned, skip. 3) Determine if effective leaf: check all children are in pruned set or node has no children. 4) If effective leaf and depth > L, add to pruned set and remove from parent's children. 5) Continue. Time O(n log n) for sorting, O(n) processing; space O(n). Connection: This feeds into L0 by providing the pruning logic after BFS collection. Common mistakes: Forgetting to update parent references after pruning, or not checking effective leaf status correctly (must consider pruned children). Real pattern: Use sorted list and set for pruned nodes.

Pseudocode:
function processNodes(nodes, L):
    nodes.sort(key=lambda x: x.depth, reverse=True)
    pruned = set()
    for node in nodes:
        if node in pruned:
            continue
        is_leaf = (not node.children) or all(child in pruned for child in node.children)
        if is_leaf and node.depth > L:
            pruned.add(node)
            if node.parent:
                node.parent.children.remove(node)
    return pruned

This core logic embodies the greedy strategy: when multiple nodes could be pruned to satisfy constraints, always choose the deepest one first. Intuition: In a tree, removing a deep node automatically shortens all paths through it, potentially fixing multiple violations at once with single removal. For instance, if a leaf at depth 5 violates L=3, pruning it might make its parent at depth 4 a new leaf; if parent still violates, we prune it next—but by starting deep, we avoid unnecessary pruning of shallower nodes. This is locally optimal because at each step, pruning the deepest violating node reduces the maximum depth impact. Algorithm: Given set of violating leaves, pick one with max depth, prune it, update tree, repeat. Time O(n log n) if sorting depths; space O(n). Connection: This logic is implemented in L1's processing order. Common mistakes: Pruning shallow nodes first might require more removals (e.g., pruning a depth-2 node when a depth-3 child also violates). Real pattern: Sort violations by depth descending.

